## Example of statement
["A vinyl enthusiast and a collector at heart! Congratulations on your new rare record from Electric Storm! Proper storage and display are crucial to maintaining the condition and value of your vinyl collection. I'd be happy to offer some advice.\n\n**Storage:**\n\n1. **Keep them upright**: Store your records vertically to prevent warping or bending. This is especially important for rare or valuable records.\n2. **Use protective sleeves**: Invest in acid-free, archival-quality inner sleeves and outer sleeves to prevent scratches and damage. You can also use polypropylene or polyethylene sleeves, which are more durable and resistant to chemicals.\n3. **Store in a cool, dry place**: Avoid storing your records in areas with direct sunlight, high humidity, or extreme temperatures (above 70°F or below 50°F).\n4. **Avoid stacking**: Try to store your records individually or in small stacks (no more than 5-6 records) to prevent pressure on the bottom records.\n5. **Use a record storage box or crate**: Consider investing in a sturdy, specifically designed record storage box or crate to keep your collection organized and protected.\n\n**Display:**\n\n1. **Use a record display stand**: Look for a sturdy, adjustable stand that can hold your record securely without putting pressure on the cover or vinyl.\n2. **Avoid direct sunlight**: If possible, display your record in a shaded area or use UV-filtering glass or acrylic to prevent fading or damage.\n3. **Handle with care**: Always handle your records by the edges, never by the center label. Use clean, dry hands or gloves to prevent oils and dirt from damaging the vinyl.\n4. **Consider a record frame**: If you want to display your record on a wall, use a frame specifically designed for vinyl records. These frames usually have a UV-filtering glass or acrylic and a sturdy backing to prevent warping.\n\n**Additional Tips:**\n\n* Clean your records regularly using a soft, dry cloth or a record cleaning brush to prevent dust buildup.\n* Avoid touching the vinyl surface as much as possible, as oils from your skin can attract dust and dirt.\n* Consider cataloging and grading your records to keep track of their condition and value.\n* If you plan to sell your records in the future, keep the original packaging, inserts, and any other materials that came with the record.\n\nIt's great to hear about your experience with the Galactic Heroes figurine! Proper storage and care can indeed increase the value of your collectibles.\n\nI hope these tips help you enjoy your Electric Storm record and maintain its condition for years to come!", "PVC pipes are a great choice for building a mini greenhouse frame. They're durable, lightweight, and easy to work with. Here are some tips on how to connect PVC pipes together to create a sturdy structure:\n\n**Choosing the Right Fittings:**\n\n1. **Use PVC pipe fittings**: Make sure to use PVC pipe fittings specifically designed for PVC pipes. They come in various shapes and sizes, such as elbows, tees, couplings, and adapters.\n2. **Select the right type of fitting**: Choose fittings that match the type of pipe you're using (e.g., schedule 40, schedule 80, or CPVC).\n3. **Consider using push-fit fittings**: Push-fit fittings are easy to use and don't require glue or primer. They're perfect for DIY projects like a mini greenhouse.\n\n**Connecting PVC Pipes:**\n\n1. **Clean and deburr the pipes**: Clean the ends of the pipes and remove any burrs or debris to ensure a secure fit.\n2. **Apply PVC primer and cement**: If you're using glue-on fittings, apply PVC primer to the pipes and fittings, followed by PVC cement. Make sure to follow the manufacturer's instructions.\n3. **Assemble the fittings**: Connect the pipes to the fittings, making sure they're fully seated and secure.\n4. **Use pipe clamps or straps**: For added security, use pipe clamps or straps to hold the pipes together, especially at joints and corners.\n\n**Tips for Building a Sturdy Frame:**\n\n1. **Use a sturdy base**: Create a solid base for your greenhouse using a PVC pipe frame or a wooden platform.\n2. **Use a square or rectangular shape**: A square or rectangular shape provides more stability than a triangular shape.\n3. **Use diagonal bracing**: Add diagonal bracing to the frame to provide additional stability and prevent sagging.\n4. **Use a ridge beam**: Add a ridge beam along the top of the frame to provide additional support and help distribute wind loads.\n5. **Anchor the frame**: Anchor the frame to the ground or a solid surface to prevent it from shifting or toppling over.\n\n**Additional Tips:**\n\n1. **Use a level**: Ensure the frame is level and plumb to prevent water from accumulating and to maintain structural integrity.\n2. **Use a measuring tape and string**: Use a measuring tape and string to help you measure and align the pipes accurately.\n3. **Work in small sections**: Build the frame in small sections, starting from the base and working your way up.\n4. **Use a drill and bits**: Use a drill and bits to make holes for screws or rivets, if needed.\n5. **Consult online resources**: If you're new to working with PVC pipes, consult online resources or tutorials for additional guidance and inspiration.\n\nBy following these tips, you'll be able to create a sturdy and functional PVC pipe frame for your mini greenhouse. Happy building!", 'The specific details about where the woman in Australia was bitten or scratched by the bat that transmitted the virus are not publicly available, so it is not clear where on her body the virus entered.\n\nAs for the autopsy findings, I could not find any specific information about the course the virus took through her body. However, it is known that after the virus enters the body, it travels to the nervous system, where it can cause inflammation and damage. This can result in a range of symptoms, including fever, headache, muscle weakness, and paralysis, depending on the severity of the infection.\n\nStudies of the virus have provided insights into its life cycle and the threat it poses to hosts. Like other viruses in the lyssavirus family, bat lyssavirus is able to replicate in nerve cells, which allows it to establish a persistent infection in the host. This may contribute to the long incubation period and the ability of the virus to remain dormant in the host for an extended period of time.\n\nResearch on bat lyssavirus has also highlighted the importance of public awareness and appropriate management of the risks associated with contact with bats and other wildlife. This includes the development of guidelines for handling and caring for animals, as well as education and outreach programs to promote public awareness of the risks and prevention measures.']

