['Sure, here is a revised summary of the training programs and drills that have been suggested in this thread:\n\n1. White belt to blue belt BJJ training program:\n* Week 1: Guard position\n* Week 2: Side control position\n* Week 3: Closed guard position\n* Week 4: Half guard position\n* Week 5: Knee-on-belly position\n* Week 6: Mount position\n* Week 7: Mount position\n* Week 8: Back control\n* Week 9: Takedowns\n* Week 10: Passes\n* Week 11: Submissions\n* Week 12: Transitions\n* Week 13: Drilling\n* Week 14: Sparring\n* Week 15: Conditioning\n2. Four-week training program focused on submissions, grips, and the kimura:\n* Week 1: Fundamentals of submissions\n* Week 2: Gi grips and control\n* Week 3: Kimura attacks and defenses\n* Week 4: Theory and visualization\n3. Good drills for BJJ that can be performed at home:\n* Shrimping\n* Knee cutters\n* Bridge and roll\n* Guard retention\n* Dynamic stretching\n* Jumping jacks\n* Lunges\n\nRemember to always warm up before training, and to listen to your body and take regular breaks to avoid injury. Also, be sure to continue learning and improving your skills and techniques in BJJ, and enjoy the journey of growth and self-improvement.', 'Here is a continuation of the hypothetical scenario featuring the characters Jerry, Kramer, and Elaine from the TV show Seinfeld, with Newman returning to his apartment as though he never left it:\n\nAs Newman returns to his apartment, he feels a sense of wonder and amazement. He can\'t believe what he has just experienced, and he can\'t believe that he can fly. He is filled with excitement and joy, and he can\'t wait to share his news with his friends.\n\nAs he enters his apartment, he sees that the gang is still there, partying and having a good time. Kramer, Elaine, Jerry, and George are all smiling and laughing, and they don\'t seem to notice that Newman is back.\n\nNewman: *smiles* "Hey guys! Look at me! I can fly!"\n\nKramer: *looks up* "What? Who are you?"\n\nElaine: *looks up* "What? Who is that?"\n\nJerry: *looks up* "Newman? Is that you?"\n\nNewman: *smiles* "Yeah, it\'s me! I can fly! I passed the test! I overcame my fears and my doubts! I\'m a better person now!"\n\nKramer: *looks confused* "What are you talking about, Newman? What test? What fears and doubts?"\n\nNewman: *smiles* "I went on a journey with The Spirit of Gloopernuts Past, and he showed me that I can do anything if I set my mind to it. I can overcome my fears and my doubts, and I can be a better person. And now, I can fly!"\n\nKramer, Elaine, Jerry, and George all stare at Newman in amazement, and then they start laughing.\n\nKramer: *laughs* "Oh, Newman. You and your crazy stories. You\'re always making things up."\n\nElaine: *laughs* "Yeah, Newman. You always have some wild tale to tell. You\'re such a funny guy."\n\nJerry: *laughs* "Yeah, Newman. You always know how to make us laugh. You\'re such a character."\n\nNewman: *frowns* "What? What do you mean? This isn\'t a story! This is real! I really can fly! Look!"\n\nAnd with that, Newman takes off into the air, flying around the room and soaring over the heads of his friends. They all stare in amazement as he flies, and then they start laughing again.\n\nKramer: *laughs* "Oh, Newman. You\'re such a riot. Keep it up, buddy. You\'re always good for a laugh."\n\nNewman: *frowns* "What? What do you mean? This isn\'t a joke! This is real! I really can fly!"\n\nBut no matter what Newman says, his friends don\'t believe him. They just keep laughing and joking, and they don\'t take him seriously.\n\nNewman: *sighs* "Fine. Have it your way. I\'ll just fly off and leave you all behind. I don\'t need your laughter and your jokes. I\'ll find people who will believe me and who will take me seriously.', "Investors can take on an active or passive role in the businesses they fund, depending on their preference and the needs of the company. Some investors prefer to take an active role, while others are content with a more passive approach.\n\nActive investors typically provide more than just financial backing; they may take a seat on the board of directors, provide strategic guidance and mentorship, and may even involve themselves in day-to-day operations. These investors are often experienced business leaders who bring their business knowledge, industry contacts, and their expertise to help the company grow and succeed.\n\nPassive investors, on the other hand, are content to take a more hands-off approach. They provide the necessary funding, but leave the day-to-day decision-making to the company's management team. These investors typically do not take an active role in the company's affairs, except for monitoring and assessment of progress.\n\nUltimately, the level of involvement an investor takes in a company will depend on the needs of the company and the investor's objectives. An investor who takes an active role may be more suited to a fledgling startup, while a more passive approach may be appropriate for a more established company that needs just the right financial backing to grow."]

