['Excellent choices! Both "We Are Legion (We Are Bob)" and "The Stainless Steel Rat" are hilarious and entertaining books that share some similarities with "The Hitchhiker\'s Guide to the Galaxy" in terms of their humor, satire, and sci-fi settings. Here\'s a brief overview of each book and why I think they\'re similar to "Hitchhiker\'s Guide":\n\n**We Are Legion (We Are Bob)** by Dennis E. Taylor:\n\nThis book follows the story of Bob Johansson, a software engineer who signs up to have his consciousness uploaded into a computer after his death. However, things don\'t go as planned, and Bob finds himself duplicated into millions of copies, each inhabiting a spaceship in a distant part of the galaxy. The Bobs, as they call themselves, must navigate the complexities of space exploration, alien encounters, and corporate bureaucracy, all while trying to maintain their sanity and individuality.\n\nSimilarities to "Hitchhiker\'s Guide":\n\n* Humor: "We Are Legion" has a similar brand of humor to "Hitchhiker\'s Guide," with a focus on witty banter, satire, and absurd situations.\n* Sci-fi setting: Both books explore the absurdities of space travel and the consequences of humanity\'s expansion into the galaxy.\n* Lighthearted tone: Despite dealing with complex themes, "We Are Legion" maintains a lighthearted and humorous tone, similar to "Hitchhiker\'s Guide."\n\n**The Stainless Steel Rat** by Harry Harrison:\n\nThis classic sci-fi novel follows the adventures of Slippery Jim diGriz, a charismatic con artist and thief who is recruited by the authorities to help them deal with a series of intergalactic crimes. Jim\'s adventures take him to various planets, where he encounters a range of bizarre characters, including a gang of space pirates, a group of humanoid robots, and a beautiful but deadly assassin.\n\nSimilarities to "Hitchhiker\'s Guide":\n\n* Humor: "The Stainless Steel Rat" has a similar sense of humor to "Hitchhiker\'s Guide," with a focus on witty one-liners, satire, and absurd situations.\n* Sci-fi setting: Both books explore the absurdities of space travel and the consequences of humanity\'s expansion into the galaxy.\n* Anti-hero protagonist: Both Arthur Dent and Slippery Jim diGriz are lovable but flawed protagonists who find themselves in absurd situations and must use their wits to survive.\n\nBoth "We Are Legion (We Are Bob)" and "The Stainless Steel Rat" share a similar tone and sense of humor with "The Hitchhiker\'s Guide to the Galaxy," and are likely to appeal to fans of Douglas Adams\' style. If you enjoy humorous sci-fi with a lighthearted tone, you\'ll likely love these books!', "Congratulations on taking the next step to leverage Instagram Live!\n\nRegarding your concern about reducing screen time and staying focused, I think website blockers or app blockers can be a fantastic tool to help you achieve your goal. These tools can help you stay on track by blocking distracting websites or apps during certain times of the day or for a set period.\n\nHere are some benefits of using website blockers or app blockers:\n\n1. **Increased productivity**: By blocking distracting websites or apps, you can focus on your tasks and be more productive.\n2. **Reduced screen time**: By limiting your access to messaging apps like WhatsApp, you can reduce your overall screen time and develop healthier habits.\n3. **Improved time management**: Website blockers or app blockers can help you prioritize your tasks and manage your time more effectively.\n4. **Enhanced self-control**: By setting boundaries for yourself, you can develop greater self-control and make more intentional decisions about how you spend your time.\n5. **Better work-life balance**: By limiting your access to work-related apps or websites during non-work hours, you can maintain a better work-life balance and reduce the risk of burnout.\n\nSome popular website blockers or app blockers you can consider include:\n\n1. Freedom: A popular app that blocks distracting websites and apps across all your devices.\n2. SelfControl: A free, open-source app for Mac that blocks distracting websites and emails.\n3. StayFocusd: A Chrome extension that blocks distracting websites and sets time limits for specific sites.\n4. Cold Turkey: A Windows app that blocks distracting websites and apps, with features like scheduling and customizable block lists.\n5. Moment: An app that tracks your screen time and provides tools to help you set goals and limits for your device use.\n\nRemember, website blockers or app blockers are tools to help you develop healthy habits and stay focused. It's essential to set goals and boundaries for yourself and use these tools to support your intentions.\n\nBy combining these tools with your newfound enthusiasm for Instagram Live, you'll be unstoppable!", 'Reaching out to groups and asking about their experience with novel writing is a great idea! It\'s essential to find a group that understands and supports your specific writing goals.\n\nRegarding mentioning your previous experience with a writing group, it\'s a bit of a gray area. Here are some pros and cons to consider:\n\n**Pros:**\n\n1. **Honesty**: By mentioning your past experience, you\'re being transparent about your intentions and showing that you\'re not afraid to share your story.\n2. **Context**: It might help the group leaders or members understand your perspective and what you\'re looking for in a writing group.\n3. **Self-awareness**: You\'re demonstrating that you\'re reflective and willing to learn from your past experiences.\n\n**Cons:**\n\n1. **Potential bias**: Some group leaders or members might view your previous experience as a red flag, wondering if you\'re flaky or not committed to a group.\n2. **Negative impression**: If you didn\'t attend the previous group\'s meeting, it might give the impression that you\'re not reliable or serious about your writing.\n3. **Unnecessary information**: It might not be relevant to your current search for a writing group, and you don\'t want to distract from your main goal of finding a suitable group.\n\nUltimately, it\'s up to you to decide whether to share this information. If you do decide to mention it, try to frame it in a positive light, focusing on what you learned from the experience and what you\'re looking for in a group now. For example:\n\n"Hi, I\'m reaching out to explore your writing group because I\'m interested in finding a community that focuses on novel writing. I was previously invited to a writing group, but it didn\'t end up being a good fit for me. I\'m looking for a group that can provide constructive feedback and support for novelists. Can you tell me more about your group\'s experience with novel writing and what kind of support you offer?"\n\nBy sharing your experience in a concise and positive way, you can show that you\'re reflective and committed to finding the right group for your writing needs.\n\nRemember, the goal is to find a group that aligns with your writing goals and provides the support you need. Focus on asking questions about the group\'s focus, format, and expectations, and don\'t be afraid to ask for clarification or more information. Good luck!']

