["Sure, here are some video game characters voiced by Troy Baker:\n\n1. Joel in The Last of Us\n2. Booker DeWitt in BioShock Infinite\n3. Rhys in Tales from the Borderlands\n4. Pagan Min in Far Cry 4\n5. Talion in Middle-earth: Shadow of Mordor\n6. Kanji Tatsumi in Persona 4\n7. Snow in Final Fantasy XIII\n8. The Joker in Batman: Arkham Origins\n9. Sam Drake in Uncharted 4: A Thief's End\n10. Higgs in Death Stranding.", "Recap of Sales Call Transcript Part 1 (0-10m9s):\n\nIn the first 10 minutes of the sales call, Matt Brown, an account executive from Fellow, introduced himself and explained that he had previously worked with some teams at the client's company. Eric Cameron, VP of People Operations, mentioned that they were exploring Fellow as a potential platform for their organization-wide one-on-ones.\n\nNick Sarkesian, Director of Business Applications, Trina Berks, Technical Program Manager, and Lucas Cooper, Business Applications Manager, were also present in the call. They were interested in understanding more about the security aspects and integrations, particularly with Okta and Workday.\n\nMatt explained the differences between the Pro and Enterprise plans of Fellow, stating that the Enterprise plan is designed for company-wide deployments, has more robust security and integrations, and offers additional features such as analytics and OKR tracking. Matt also mentioned that Fellow could be a single source of truth for tracking OKRs and other important information.\n\nNick inquired about the process for uploading and managing OKRs within Fellow. Matt responded that Fellow's analytics can be tailored for the entire organization or individual teams, and they will work with the senior leadership team to import objectives within the platform.\n\nAt the end of this section of the call, Matt agreed to send over the necessary security documentation, integration information, and an NDA as a follow-up to the conversation.", "That's a great idea! Inviting Coach Rachel to join you for a casual tennis session at Oakwood Park sounds like a lot of fun.\n\nAs for court reservations, it's always a good idea to check with the park or tennis facility beforehand to confirm their policies. However, in general, many public parks like Oakwood Park have open courts that are available on a first-come, first-served basis.\n\nIf you're planning to play during a non-peak time, such as a weekday morning or early afternoon, you might be able to find an open court without a reservation. However, if you're planning to play during peak hours (usually weekends or evenings), it's possible that the courts might be busier, and a reservation might be a good idea.\n\nTo be safe, you could give the Oakwood Park tennis facility a quick call or check their website to confirm their court reservation policies. You could also ask Coach Rachel if she has any insight or preferences regarding court reservations.\n\nIt's also worth noting that some tennis coaches, like Coach Rachel, might have their own preferences or requirements for court reservations, especially if they're planning to conduct a lesson or session with you. So, it's always a good idea to check with her directly to see what she recommends.\n\nOverall, I think it's a great idea to invite Coach Rachel to join you for a casual tennis session, and with a little planning, you should be able to find a court that works for everyone!"]

