['States with legalized marijuana have implemented a range of regulations and monitoring systems to ensure public safety. Here are some examples:\n\n1. Age Restrictions: Every state with legalized marijuana has age restrictions in place to prevent underage access. This includes strict regulations for dispensaries and requiring ID checks for all customers.\n\n2. Product Testing: Many states require that all marijuana products be tested for purity, potency, and contaminants by third-party laboratories. This helps to ensure that customers receive high-quality, safe products and avoid any harmful contaminants.\n\n3. Packaging and Labeling: States have implemented specific packaging and labeling requirements to ensure that customers can make informed decisions about what they are purchasing. This includes clear labeling of potency, ingredients, and suggested dosages.\n\n4. License and Compliance Monitoring: Marijuana facilities are required to obtain licenses and adhere to strict guidelines for operation. These facilities are subject to unannounced inspections by regulatory authorities to ensure they are complying with these guidelines.\n\n5. Tracking Systems: Many states have implemented sophisticated tracking systems to monitor marijuana from seed to sale. This helps to prevent illegal diversion of marijuana products and ensure that only legal products are being sold.\n\n6. Fines and Penalties: States have implemented strict penalties and fines for businesses and individuals that violate regulations related to legal marijuana sales and use.\n\nIn conclusion, legalized marijuana is regulated and monitored through a variety of systems and regulations to ensure public safety. These systems include age restrictions, product testing, packaging and labeling requirements, compliance monitoring, and tracking systems. However, it is important to note that these monitoring systems are not foolproof, and concerns linger around the potency of products and contaminants that could negatively impact public health.', 'Sure, here are the categories, their descriptions, and 5 examples of coins for each:\n\n1. Payments: Coins designed for peer-to-peer transactions and for paying for goods and services.\nExamples: Bitcoin (BTC), Litecoin (LTC), Bitcoin Cash (BCH), Dash (DASH), Nano (NANO).\n2. Privacy: Coins that prioritize privacy and anonymity in transactions.\nExamples: Monero (XMR), Zcash (ZEC), Dash (DASH), Pirate Chain (ARRR), Verge (XVG).\n3. Smart Contracts: Coins that', 'CDHR Article 22: "Everyone shall have the right to express his opinion freely in such manner as would not be contrary to the principles of the Shari\'ah. Everyone shall have the right to advocate what is right, and propagate what is good, and warn against what is wrong and evil according to the norms of Islamic Shari\'ah."\n\nComment: CDHR Article 22 does not directly address the idea of the prohibition of retroactive penal legislation and the prohibition of imposing heavier penalties than those applicable at the time of the offense. Instead, it emphasizes the right to express one\'s opinion freely, subject to the principles of the Shari\'ah. This differs from the UDHR Article 15, which specifically addresses the prohibition of retroactive penal legislation and the prohibition of imposing heavier penalties than those applicable at the time of the offense.']

